      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Rental Property Owners Can Claim as Tax Deductions in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        If you are selling an investment property in Brisbane, understanding what you have claimed, and what those claims mean for your capital gain, is essential before you list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Many of Daniel's clients in Brisbane's inner east are not first-time sellers. They are investors selling a rental property they have owned for several years, often while simultaneously managing a purchase. Before any of those conversations get to price guides and marketing, the question that tends to surface early is: what do I need to know about my tax position going into the sale? This guide covers the main deductions available on a Queensland rental property and, critically, what happens to those deductions when you sell.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The main categories of deductible expenses</h2>
      <p>For a Queensland residential rental property held in the name of an individual or a trust, the deductible expenses during the rental period generally include the following categories. Each has specific rules, so the list below is a guide to the structure, not a substitute for professional advice on your specific circumstances.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interest on the investment loan.</strong> For most leveraged investors, this is the largest single deduction. Interest on borrowings used to acquire or improve the property is deductible in the year it is incurred. If you have a line of credit or redraw facility and have mixed personal and investment use, only the investment portion is deductible, and the ATO expects you to be able to demonstrate the split.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Property management fees.</strong> Fees charged by a property manager for finding tenants, managing the tenancy, and handling routine maintenance are fully deductible in the year incurred. Leasing fees (charged when a new tenancy starts) are also deductible.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Council rates and water rates.</strong> The landlord's portion of council rates and any water usage charges the landlord is responsible for under the tenancy agreement are deductible. Queensland tenants typically pay water consumption above a base allocation, so check your tenancy agreement to understand what you are actually bearing.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Land tax.</strong> If land tax applies to your property (which depends on the total unimproved value of land you own in Queensland), it is deductible as a rental expense in the year it is assessed. Land tax thresholds in Queensland change periodically, so confirm the current threshold with a property tax specialist.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance premiums.</strong> Landlord insurance and building insurance (for a stand-alone property) are deductible. Contents insurance is deductible to the extent the contents are provided for the tenant's use (appliances, window coverings). Your own personal contents are not deductible.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Repairs and maintenance.</strong> Genuine repairs to the existing structure or fittings, meaning restoring something to its original condition rather than improving it, are fully deductible in the year they are carried out. This category is commonly misunderstood, and the distinction between repairs and capital improvements is important enough that it is covered in a separate guide on this site.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Advertising for tenants.</strong> Costs of advertising a vacancy, whether through a property management platform or elsewhere, are deductible.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Depreciation: Division 43 and Division 40.</strong> This is where the deductions become more technical. Division 43 covers the building allowance, typically 2.5% per year of the original construction cost, for residential buildings constructed after July 1985. Division 40 covers plant and equipment, individual items within the property such as air conditioning units, dishwashers, and hot water systems, claimed at the effective life depreciation rate for each item. A quantity surveyor's depreciation schedule is usually required to substantiate these claims, particularly Division 43.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The interaction between deductions and your capital gain</h2>
      <p>This is the part that catches investors off guard most often. The deductions you claim during the rental period do not simply reduce your income each year and disappear. Division 43 building allowance deductions reduce the cost base of your property, which increases the taxable capital gain at sale. If you have claimed $40,000 in building allowance over ten years, $40,000 of cost base has been removed, and your capital gain at sale will be $40,000 higher as a result.</p>

      <p>Division 40 plant and equipment items purchased before 9 May 2017 may also affect your cost base calculations. Items purchased after that date by investors are subject to different rules following legislative changes. Your accountant will need to work through the specific items on your depreciation schedule and how they were acquired to calculate this correctly.</p>

      <p>For properties owned longer than twelve months, the 50% CGT discount for individuals still applies to the remaining gain after cost base adjustments, but the base calculation needs to be right before the discount is applied. Getting this wrong, typically by underestimating how much cost base has been reduced by depreciation claims, leads to an unexpected tax liability at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Partial year deductions when you sell</h2>
      <p>If you sell the property partway through a financial year, deductions are proportional to the rental period within that year. A property tenanted from 1 July to 15 March and then vacated for sale preparation from 15 March to settlement (say, 30 June) would have deductible expenses limited to the period the property was available for rent. Holding costs during the vacancy and sale preparation period are not deductible as rental expenses, though they may be added to the cost base depending on the nature of the expense.</p>

      <p>This proportioning affects interest, rates, insurance, and management fees. It does not affect depreciation claims in quite the same way, because depreciation is typically calculated on the days the property was used for income-producing purposes during the year.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why an accountant experienced in investment property is essential</h2>
      <p>The interaction between rental deductions, cost base adjustments, and CGT is not a straightforward calculation. The variables include the original purchase price and acquisition costs, all capital improvements made during ownership and how they were categorised, the total depreciation claimed across all years held, whether you held the property for more than twelve months, whether you have any carried-forward capital losses from other assets, and your marginal income tax rate in the year of sale.</p>

      <p>A general practitioner accountant who does not regularly handle investment property transactions can easily miss cost base adjustments or apply the wrong depreciation treatment. The stakes are high: an error of $30,000 in the cost base calculation at a 24.5% effective tax rate on the discounted gain (half of a 49% marginal rate) costs approximately $7,350 in additional tax. That is before interest and penalties if the ATO audits the return.</p>

      <p>Daniel regularly works with vendors selling investment properties across Brisbane's inner east. The practical advice he gives consistently is this: before you start thinking seriously about what your property might sell for, get a preliminary discussion with your accountant about your likely tax position on sale. It does not need to be a formal tax advice document at that stage. It does need to be enough of a conversation that you understand the rough net proceeds after CGT, so that your financial planning around the sale and any subsequent purchase is based on realistic numbers.</p>

